<section class="hero">
  <div class="wrap">
    <p class="eyebrow">MCP gateway &amp; router</p>
    <h1>{{ site.tagline }}</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      Install <a href="https://modelcontextprotocol.io">Model Context Protocol</a> servers from registries
      or npm, run them locally as lazily-spawned child processes (or proxy remote ones), and re-expose every
      one over streamable HTTP. Point a single client at the router instead of configuring N servers everywhere.
    </p>
    <div class="cta-row">
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="#quickstart">Get started</a>
      <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="{{ site.repo }}">View on GitHub ↗</a>
    </div>

    <div class="endpoint-card" aria-hidden="false">
      <div class="endpoint-row">
        <span class="method">GET</span>
        <code>http://host:3000/mcp/&lt;name&gt;</code>
        <span class="endpoint-note">one server</span>
      </div>
      <div class="endpoint-row">
        <span class="method method-agg">ALL</span>
        <code>http://host:3000/mcp</code>
        <span class="endpoint-note">every server, merged</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="wrap">
    <h2>What it does</h2>
    <div class="feature-grid">
      <div class="feature">
        <div class="feature-icon">🧩</div>
        <h3>Install from anywhere</h3>
        <p>Browse the official MCP registry (or any compatible one), install directly from npm, or proxy a
          remote streamable-HTTP server. One file per server under <code>DATA_DIR/config</code>.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="feature">
        <div class="feature-icon">🔀</div>
        <h3>Two ways to connect</h3>
        <p>Hit <code>/mcp/&lt;name&gt;</code> for a single server, or the aggregate <code>/mcp</code> that
          merges every enabled server with <code>&lt;server&gt;__&lt;tool&gt;</code> namespacing.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="feature">
        <div class="feature-icon">🗂️</div>
        <h3>Custom aggregates</h3>
        <p>Group a chosen subset of servers into a <strong>project</strong> at its own
          <code>/mcp/p/&lt;slug&gt;</code> URL — with optional per-project env, args, and header overrides. Each
          client gets exactly the tools it needs.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="feature">
        <div class="feature-icon">💤</div>
        <h3>Lazy &amp; warm</h3>
        <p>stdio servers spawn on first request, stay warm, and shut down after an idle timeout (default 5
          minutes, per-server override). No idle processes hanging around.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="feature">
        <div class="feature-icon">🔐</div>
        <h3>One token, one door</h3>
        <p>A single bearer token guards the management API and every MCP endpoint. Disable it for trusted
          local networks with <code>SECURE_LOCAL_NET=true</code>.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="feature">
        <div class="feature-icon">🖥️</div>
        <h3>Web UI or JSON</h3>
        <p>Manage registries, installs, and per-server env/API keys from the built-in React UI — or hand-edit
          the flat JSON config and reload.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="feature">
        <div class="feature-icon">📦</div>
        <h3>Ships as one image</h3>
        <p>A single Docker image builds the app and server; Express serves the UI. <code>docker compose up</code>
          with a <code>./data</code> volume and you're live.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-alt">
  <div class="wrap">
    <h2>How it works</h2>
    <div class="flow">
      <div class="flow-node flow-client">
        <strong>Your MCP client</strong>
        <span>Claude Code, Claude Desktop, any streamable-HTTP client</span>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-arrow">→ <code>/mcp</code> →</div>
      <div class="flow-node flow-router">
        <strong>MCP Router</strong>
        <span>auth · routing · lazy spawn · aggregation</span>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-node flow-servers">
        <strong>Downstream servers</strong>
        <span>stdio child processes &amp; remote HTTP servers</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="flow-caption">
      The router validates the bearer token, forwards <code>tools</code>/<code>resources</code>/<code>prompts</code>
      1:1 for per-server routes, and for the aggregate merges every enabled server's capabilities — stripping the
      <code>&lt;server&gt;__</code> prefix on each call to route it back to the owning server.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

